In Spring Data JPA / Hibernate ORM, Generators are used to automatically generate primary key values for entity objects.

Instead of manually setting the ID, the framework generates it automatically.

1️⃣ @GeneratedValue Annotation

The most common way to generate IDs.

Example:

@Id
@GeneratedValue
private Integer empId;

This tells JPA:

Automatically generate primary key value
2️⃣ Types of Generators

@GeneratedValue supports several strategies.

Strategy	Description
AUTO	JPA chooses best strategy
IDENTITY	Database auto-increment
SEQUENCE	Uses database sequence
TABLE	Uses separate table for ID generation
3️⃣ AUTO Strategy
@Id
@GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.AUTO)
private Integer id;

JPA automatically decides which method to use.

4️⃣ IDENTITY Strategy

Commonly used with MySQL.

@Id
@GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
private Integer id;

Database generates ID using AUTO_INCREMENT.

Example SQL table:

id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY
5️⃣ SEQUENCE Strategy

Used mainly in Oracle / PostgreSQL.

@Id
@GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.SEQUENCE)
private Integer id;

It uses a database sequence object.

6️⃣ TABLE Strategy

Uses a separate table to store ID values.

@Id
@GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.TABLE)
private Integer id;

Less commonly used.

Example Entity
@Entity
public class Employee {

    @Id
    @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
    private Integer empId;

    private String empName;
}
How It Works

When inserting:

insert into employee(emp_name) values ('Rishav');

Database automatically generates:

emp_id = 1

Next record:

emp_id = 2
Short Interview Answer

Generators in JPA are used to automatically generate primary key values using @GeneratedValue with strategies like AUTO, IDENTITY, SEQUENCE, and TABLE.
